The paper proposes a new type of neural network architecture that uses binary-valued weights, biases, and inputs, and relies on bitwise operations instead of floating or fixed-point arithmetic. This makes it particularly suitable for resource-constrained environments, such as embedded systems or mobile devices. The paper also proposes several training schemes to optimize the performance of the network, including weight compression and noisy backpropagation. The experiments focus on image classification using the MNIST dataset, which suggests that the proposed architecture is well-suited for computer vision tasks. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.SY (Systems and Control).
